f Cases -- tIndex of Statutes, Treaties and Agreements -- tLaw and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDelgamuukw. Mabo. Ngati Apa. Recent cases have created a framework for litigating Aboriginal title in Canada, Australia, and New Zealand. This book brings together distinguished scholars who show that our understanding of where the concept of Aboriginal title came from – and where it may be going – can also be enhanced by exploring legal developments in these former British colonies in a comparative, multidisciplinary framework. Contributors trace the role that courts and legislatures played in the extinguishment and acquisition of Aboriginal title and land. They then establish that although each country’s development was distinctive, common issues shaped – and continue to inform – indigenous peoples’ struggle for recognition. This path-breaking book offers a perspective on Aboriginal title that extends beyond national borders to consider similar developments in common law countries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh1 aBallantyne, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartrand, Paul L.A.H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchins, Peter W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnafla, Louis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnafla, Louis A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMatsui, Kenichi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNeil, Kent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Nicolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRay, Arthur